hibits a large linear polarization degree\ndue to magnetospheric synchrotron emission. The analysis of NIR polarimetry\ndata combined with the radiative transfer modelling shows that the DSO is a\npeculiar source of compact nature in the S cluster $(r \\lesssim 0.04\\,{\\rm\npc})$. It is most probably a young stellar object embedded in a non-spherical\ndusty envelope, whose components include optically thick dusty envelope,\nbipolar cavities, and a bow shock. Alternatively, the continuum emission could\nbe of a non-thermal origin due to the presence of a young neutron star and its\nwind nebula.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Apr 2017 11:04:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-06-28"}
